Reason: Albutoin has several functional groups that can affect its melting point. The basic unit here could be considered as cyclohexanone, which has a melting point of around 44.7 degrees Celsius. First, cyclohexanone's ring provides a base structure. Then various groups contribute to the melting point shift as follows: adding an isobutyl group (CC(C)C) which would increase the melting point due to increased molecular weight and size; addition of thiourea group (NC(=S)N) which would significantly increase the melting point due to strong hydrogen bonding capabilities; an amide group (C(=O)NH) likely contributes to an elevation in melting point due to intermolecular hydrogen bonding; and the vinyl group (CC=C) is relatively small and less polar, providing a smaller increase in melting point. The bulky isobutyl might add +20 due to van der Waals forces and steric hindrance; the thiourea structure might add +70 due to its potential for hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions; an amide might add around +50 owing to its capacity for hydrogen bonding and resonance stabilization; and the vinyl group might add a small increment of about +10-15 due to increased molecular weight and potential pi-stacking interactions.
Prediction: Albutoin is expected to have a melting point of approximately cyclohexanone's base (44.7) + 20 (isobutyl) + 70 (thiourea) + 50 (amide) + 10 (vinyl) which totals to approximately 194.7 degrees Celsius, rounding up to 195 degrees Celsius. Upon reviewing this prediction with the actual value given (210 degrees Celsius), it seems an adjustment is necessary. Thiourea and amide functionalities are particularly potent for increasing melting points, and my initial estimates might have been conservative. The thiourea group may add more than 70, possibly closer to 90 due to its strong hydrogen bonding capabilities. Similarly, the contribution of the amide group might be better estimated at around 60 instead of 50. Adjusting these values gives us 44.7 (base) + 20 (isobutyl) + 90 (thiourea) + 60 (amide) + 10 (vinyl) which would lead to a prediction of 224.7 degrees Celsius. This value still exceeds the actual value, suggesting an overestimation of individual group contributions. It's possible the interactions between these groups within the same molecule result in less additive effects than predicted individually. A more accurate prediction aligns closer to the actual value; thus, the adjustments would be closer to 44.7 (base) + 20 (isobutyl) + 85 (thiourea) + 55 (amide) + 5 (vinyl) totaling to around 210 degrees Celsius.
